INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (8, 4, 'This chunk derives the steady-state design equation for the Blending System using mass balance equations then poses a Control Question about what happens when operating conditions deviate from design values. The design of the blending system is based on mass balance equations. The Overall Balance is given by $0 = \bar{w}_1 + \bar{w}_2 - \bar{w}$ (Eq. 1-1), and the Component A Balance is $\bar{w}_1 \bar{x}_1 + \bar{w}_2 \bar{x}_2 - \bar{w} \bar{x} = 0$ (Eq. 1-2), where overbars denote nominal steady-state design values. To find the required value of $\bar{w}_2$ to reach the set point ($\bar{x} = x_{sp}$), Equation 1-2 is solved with the assumption $\bar{x}_2 = 1$. The resulting Design Equation (Eq. 1-3) is: $$\bar{w}_2 = \bar{w}_1 \frac{x_{sp} - \bar{x}_1}{1 - x_{sp}}$$. Equation 1-3 serves as the design equation to maintain $x$ at $x_{sp}$ under ideal conditions. However, if conditions such as the inlet concentration $x_1$ changes with time to increase beyond its nominal value $\bar{x}_1$ while the manipulated flow $w_2$ remains at its design value $\bar{w}_2$, then the output $x$ will exceed the desired set point $x_{sp}$. This leads to the Control Question: How can we ensure $x$ remains at $x_{sp}$ when $x_1$ changes with time?', '[-0.025835937,0.016569577,-0.05821271,0.017984197,-0.005073285,-0.024761789,0.0074890936,0.026723236,-0.0036939478,0.03474107,-0.012900684,0.00012365557,0.009482863,-0.008893038,0.0013591916,-0.026426708,0.018680997,0.01854186,-0.015251719,-0.021240376,-0.020198146,0.0028047469,0.012575929,-0.028170196,0.009117048,0.03843621,0.0015372004,-0.0051524816,0.014989006,0.06589386,-0.023746379,-0.034014903,-0.0047999076,-0.056526426,0.024839094,-0.021444634,0.008692282,-0.021278944,-0.0355479,0.06037365,-0.022976084,-0.01368969,-0.006225784,-0.023727288,0.05201235,-0.017985838,-0.025577437,-0.058447227,-0.036532763,-0.023646483,-0.00061532855,0.015616401,0.023649331,-0.025418676,0.062085334,0.052968003