INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (9, 4, 'This chunk presents Method 1 (Feedback Control) as the strategy to the Control Problem, using the proportional control law and explaining how the controller responds to deviations in the output concentration by adjusting the manipulated variable. Control Strategy Method 1 involves measuring the output $x$ and adjusting the manipulated variable $w_2$. Intuitively, if $x$ is too high, $w_2$ (the pure A stream) should be reduced. This is implemented via a Proportional Feedback Control Law (Eq. 1-4): $$w_2(t) = \bar{w}_2 + K_c [x_{sp} - x(t)]$$. Here, $K_c$ is the controller gain. For this specific system, $K_c$ must be positive because an increase in $x$ (making $x_{sp} - x(t)$ negative) should result in a decrease in $w_2$. [VIDEO_TRANSCRIPT]: In feedback control, there is reactor which there are two inlet streams and one outlet stream. All the streams are a mixture of two chemical species, A and B. $w_1, w_2,$ and $w$ are the mass flow rates. $x_1, x_2$ and $x$ are the mass fractions of chemical species A. We are mixing the two streams to get the desired composition. The composition, which is a controlled variable, is measured with the sensor. The measured value is transmitted to the controller as an electrical signal. The controller compares this value with the set point. Based on the deviation, the controller computes and sends the value of $w_2$ to the control valve, which opens or closes accordingly.', '[-0.047809117,-0.009524667,-0.029047389,-0.00840677,-0.028319404,-0.020015411,-0.008481464,0.045871086,-0.01067307,0.05230361,-0.0563676,-0.01781328,0.0054192524,-0.0029462732,0.007441547,0.0123208305,-0.013389891,-0.008052704,0.01838068,-0.054625258,-0.004006158,-0.0027246748,0.0030668618,0.026454281,0.014440459,0.0076827016,-0.013414795,-0.00994915,0.034092296,0.061039947,0.02390468,-0.027013944,-0.03529151,-0.043132097,-0.013479253,0.017052822,0.014921421,-0.08653118,-0.030049426,0.025833018,-0.004082414,-0.025380217,0