INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (18, 9, 'This chunk introduces the fundamental concept of a process model as a mathematical representation that captures the essential knowledge of how a system behaves, emphasizing the balance between complexity and accuracy in modeling. A process model is a mathematical representation of the essential aspects of an existing system or a system to be constructed, which represents knowledge of that system in a usable form. The knowledge of the process is contained in the model, which relates inputs to outputs through differential equations of the form $\frac{dx}{dt} = f(x, u)$. The guiding principle in model development, attributed to Einstein, is that everything should be made as simple as possible, but no simpler. This principle acknowledges that model equations are at best an approximation to the real process, captured in the adage "All models are wrong, but some are useful." Modeling inherently involves a compromise between model accuracy and complexity, and the cost and effort required to develop the model. Process modeling is both an art and a science, requiring creativity to simplify assumptions while incorporating all important dynamics. Dynamic models of chemical processes typically consist of ordinary differential equations (ODE), partial differential equations (PDE), and related algebraic equations.', '[-0.035732143,-0.028440807,-0.040088538,0.0025630745,0.010234105,-0.050832815,0.0073525077,0.032354187,-0.0024511914,0.015700188,-0.04568721,-0.015194426,0.0068119527,0.017575106,-0.0027725433,0.055502437,-0.0055866865,0.023972567,0.030521384,-0.021966917,0.0033173347,-0.0049944324,0.05701225,-0.051878523,-0.010676711,0.024166532,0.0010367476,-0.012847275,0.007175134,-0.026667334,0.0029786634,0.009433455,-0.024819354,-0.015815359,-0.058568813,0.016385633,0.0142530035,-0.02856699,-0.027348652,-0.009760976,0.012340563,-0.0319478,0.016233379,-0.058200847,0.04253936,-0.014839357,-0.04698863,-0.055218983,-0.024618313,-0.04985875