INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (24, 12, 'This chunk introduces the blending process example to demonstrate how dynamic models are developed from conservation principles, deriving the unsteady-state mass and component balance equations and connecting them to the steady-state equations from Chapter 1. In the blending process illustrative example, an unsteady-state mass balance for the blending system states that the rate of accumulation of mass in the tank equals to the rate of mass in minus the rate of mass out (Equation 2-1). The mathematical formulation gives $\frac{d(V\rho)}{dt} = w_1 + w_2 - w$ (Equation 2-2), where $w_1$, $w_2$ and $w$ are mass flow rates and V is the tank volume. The unsteady-state component balance is $$\frac{d(V\rho x)}{dt} = w_1x_1 + w_2x_2 - wx$$ (Equation 2-3). The corresponding steady-state model was derived in Chapter 1 when time derivatives equal zero: $0 = \bar{w}_1 + \bar{w}_2 - w$ (Equation 2-4) and $0 = \bar{w}_1 \bar{x}_1 + \bar{w}_2 \bar{x}_2 - \bar{w} \bar{x}$ (Equation 2-5), where bars indicate nominal steady-state values.', '[-0.00370883,0.0055289804,-0.020843,0.0065706503,-0.002803927,-0.03402538,0.051904116,0.043537628,-0.0323692,0.04239751,-0.0017435661,-0.017481683,-0.016730474,0.014727809,0.015738657,0.0050447625,-0.0034144556,0.03241822,-0.01236413,-0.038713276,-0.014996775,-0.0217818,0.04000628,-0.008549692,2.5785674e-05,0.033638444,-0.011544279,-0.012158558,0.017082587,0.050685212,0.027584102,0.019936103,-0.040813547,-0.068897486,-0.006239764,0.011848216,0.010191017,-0.012272205,-0.05228896,0.05368547,0.010063846,-0.024518248,0.009817608,-0.0699831,0.06424402,-0.007974877,-0.02299763,-0.048892334,-0.020426601,-0.021641184,-0.0041482444,-0.02401702,0.0474314,-0.009236437,0.029943014,-0.0029265608,-0.06700428,0.0044516055,-0.07785939,0.009948548,-0.045365322,0.045300115,-0.01819922,0.023589881,-0.02126281,0.037340727,-0.0030391489,0.016731933,-0.019801108,-0.02941429,-0.00045665956,0.014728169,-0.011369378,-0.01987808