INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (27, 12, 'This chunk compares three different cases of the stirred-tank heating process for constant holdup (fixed volume) and variable holdup (changing volume). For Case 1 with constant holdup, only the conservation of energy is required, not mass balance. The energy balance equation is $\frac{d(U_{int})}{dt} = -\Delta(w\hat{H}) + Q$ (Equation 2-10), where $U_{int}$ is internal energy, $w$ is mass flow rate, $H$ is enthalpy per unit mass, and $Q$ is the rate of heat transfer ($Q>0$ when the system receives heat). Converting this equation gives: $V\rho C \frac{dT}{dt} = wC(T_i - T) + Q$ (Equation 2-36). For Case 2 with variable holdup, both material and energy balances are required. The material balance equation is $\frac{d(V\rho)}{dt} = w_i - w$ (Equation 2-37). The energy balance equation is $\frac{d(V\rho\hat{H})}{dt} = w_i C (T_i - T_{ref}) - w C (T - T_{ref}) + Q$ (Equation 2-40). Using the chain rule and rearranging, it gives $\frac{dV}{dt} = \frac{1}{\rho}(w_i - w)$ (Equation 2-45) and $\frac{dT}{dt} = \frac{w_i}{V\rho}(T_i - T) + \frac{Q}{\rho CV}$ (Equation 2-46). For Case 3 with constant holdup and non-instantaneous energy transfer, there is unsteady state specifically for the tank and heating element. Tank equation is $mC \frac{dT}{dt} = wC(T_i - T) + h_e A_e (T_e - T)$ (Equation 2-47). Element equation is $m_e C_e \frac{dT_e}{dt} = Q - h_e A_e (T_e - T)$ (Equation 2-48) where $m = \rho V$, $m_e C_e$ = product of mass of metal in heating element and its specific heat, and $h_e A_e$ = product of heat transfer coefficient and area available for heat transfer.', '[0.016558822,0.0010257977,-0.04650852,0.014226281,-0.0036038996,-0.048564907,0.0019705663,0.021731947,-0.011228677,-0.00093516125,0.030369978,-0.021647606,-0.015321226,0.009112546,0.005668487,-0.012825188,-0.01445045,0.02026123,-0.0069994032,-0.016524795,-0.043187786,0.007880188,0.008512294,-0.018255534,0.045876168,0.030932475,0.02108852,0.0007292208,0.020987757,0.