INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (29, 12, 'This chunk compares the three important variations of liquid storage systems. Case 1 of liquid storage systems is a constant speed pump where inlet or outlet flow rates is constant. The exit flow rate is constant and is completely independent of liquid level over wide range of conditions, making the tank operate as a flow integrator. For Case 2 of liquid storage systems where the tank exit line may function as a resistance to flow along the line. It may contain a valve that provides significant resistance at a point. Flow may be linearly related to the driving force, i.e., liquid level (Ohm’s law), where the relationship between liquid level ($h$) and flow ($q$) is described as: $$h = q R_v$ or $q = \frac{1}{R_v} h$$ (Equation 2-55), where $R_v$ is the resistance of the line or valve. Substituting Equation 2-55 into 2-54 gives the equation $$A \frac{dh}{dt} = q_i - \frac{1}{R_v} h$$ (Equation 2-57). For Case 3 of liquid storage systems where a fixed valve has been placed on the exit line and turbulent flow is assumed, the driving force for flow through a fixed valve with turbulent flow is the pressure drop $\Delta P = P - P_a$ (Equation 2-58), where $P$ is the pressure at the bottom of the tank and $P_a$ is the ambient pressure. The flow rate $q$ is assumed to be nonlinearly related to the driving force such that it is proportional to the square root of the pressure drop, given by $q = C_v^* \sqrt{P - P_a}$ (Equation 2-59). The pressure $P$ at the bottom of the tank is $P = P_a + \frac{\rho g h}{g_c}$ (Equation 2-60). Substituting equations 2-59 and 2-60 yields $$A \frac{dh}{dt} = q_i - C_v \sqrt{\frac{\rho g h}{g_c}} = q_i - C_v \sqrt{h}$$ (Equation 2-61).', '[-0.0020625773,-0.0105877565,-0.02488861,0.016073693,0.00036494492,-0.04374924,-0.028193735,0.04874368,0.005124834,0.010086538,0.0060890336,-0.00659942,-0.025645018,0.02061332,0.00023591759,0.044823255,-0.02161625,0.0027754572,-0.018965442,0.0036116457,0.0005531529,