INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (38, 15, 'This chunk details Laplace Transform Property 1 of Linearity, explaining the principle of superposition and providing examples using hyperbolic functions cosh and sinh. The Linearity property asserts that the principle of superposition holds for Laplace transforms. This means that for constants $a_1$ and $a_2$, the transform of a sum is the sum of the transforms: $\mathcal{L}[a_{1}f_{1}(t)+a_{2}f_{2}(t)]=a_{1}\mathcal{L}[f_{1}(t)]+a_{2}\mathcal{L}[f_{2}(t)]$. However, it is important to note that the Laplace transform of a product is not equal to the product of the transforms: $\mathcal{L}(f_{1}(t)f_{2}(t))\ne F_{1}(s)F_{2}(s)$. Examples of linearity include the hyperbolic cosine and sine functions. For hyperbolic cosine, defined as $\cosh ax = \frac{e^{ax}+e^{-ax}}{2}$, the transform is derived as: $$\mathcal{L}\{\cosh ax\}=\mathcal{L}\left\{\frac{e^{ax}+e^{-ax}}{2}\right\}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{s-a}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{s+a}=\frac{s}{s^{2}-a^{2}}$$. Similarly, for hyperbolic sine, defined as $\sinh ax = \frac{e^{ax}-e^{-ax}}{2}$, the transform is: $$\mathcal{L}\{\sinh ax\}=\mathcal{L}\left\{\frac{e^{ax}-e^{-ax}}{2}\right\}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{s-a}-\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{s+a}=\frac{a}{s^{2}-a^{2}}$$.', '[-0.035142872,-0.007637962,-0.027970647,0.022619875,0.005115002,0.010285202,0.018757287,0.056490656,-0.019889161,0.007852107,-0.030939214,0.0057116593,0.009683432,0.03697398,0.017538872,0.028086608,0.020622924,0.0127989175,-0.015204742,-0.025151864,-0.02573825,-0.009729785,0.0133225955,-0.0072285943,-0.019212294,-0.0012617442,0.057516288,-0.014198621,-0.007314454,0.031484812,-0.011662134,0.040836494,-0.029646965,-0.051523242,-0.030549694,-0.0012425043,-0.015203638,0.0005208957,-0.035196863,0.0031109499,-0.01987547,-0.003390854,0.009797513,-0.011614205,0.053203043,0.0042106765,0.0021815505,-0.058800507,-0.025608763,-0.0052915625,0.02473418,-0.007991648,0.046899166,-0.04262169,-0.03686991,0.0063478667,-0.033551477,-0.006224144,-0