INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (40, 15, 'This chunk explains Laplace Transform Property 3 of s-shifting, which relates multiplication by an exponential term in the time domain to a shift in the s-domain, including a proof and practical examples. Property 3, known as "s-shifting," states that if $\mathcal{L}\{f(t)\} = F(s)$, then multiplying $f(t)$ by an exponential $e^{at}$ results in shifting the s-variable by $a$: $$\mathcal{L}\{e^{at}f(t)\}=F(s-a)$$. The proof follows from the definition of the Laplace transform:$$\mathcal{L}\{e^{at}f(t)\}=\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-st}e^{at}f(t)dt = \int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-(s-a)t}f(t)dt = F(s-a)$$. If we know the Laplace transform of $f(t)$ to $F(s)$, we just replace every $s$ term in the original transform $F(s)$ with $(s-a)$. For example, to compute $\mathcal{L}\{e^{3t}\sin t\}$, knowing that $\mathcal{L}\{\sin t\}=\frac{1}{s^{2}+1}$, we replace $s$ with $(s-3)$ to get $\frac{1}{(s-3)^{2}+1}$. Conversely, for the inverse transform of $\frac{s-7}{81+(s-7)^{2}}$, observing the shift allows one to identify the solution as $e^{7t}\cos 9t$.', '[-0.023822099,0.042434778,-0.011289646,0.0069861338,-0.00010043167,-0.029100232,0.004646589,0.007215635,0.010613942,-0.0033638128,-0.011914209,0.05765363,-0.027840583,0.022511909,0.017682401,0.017878873,0.052379485,0.010125367,0.019852364,-0.011154775,-0.021763496,-0.017811416,-0.01109509,0.008694591,0.0053570173,0.005901192,0.036061436,0.0026190656,0.052682847,-0.009570595,-0.010721885,0.005817065,-0.03144555,-0.03780445,-0.0669729,0.015899742,0.01970814,0.005736474,-0.048818357,-0.0016523995,-0.02579608,-0.034623213,0.07634227,-0.014628184,0.0103311045,-0.008271276,-0.010119032,-0.064236306,-0.034354243,-0.00059126865,0.018484006,-0.016856536,0.08438706,-0.05426198,-0.0025929976,0.0012501652,-0.059193898,-0.01449214,-0.073507145,-0.026991706,-0.025229856,0.009986824,-0.034893572,-0.0146526685,0.00019237037,0.006211134,0.016602062,0.038107105,0.01340314,-0.016695123,-0.026769074,0.044911504,-0.06