INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (44, 16, 'This chunk explains the Inverse Laplace Transform and the necessity of Partial Fraction Expansion (PFE) when the transform cannot be found directly in the Laplace Transform Table. To get the time-domain solution, the inverse Laplace transform is defined as $\mathcal{L}^{-1}[F(s)] \equiv f(t)$. While simple terms like $\frac{1}{s+a}$ invert directly to $e^{-at}$ using the Laplace Transform Table, complex expressions often require decomposition. If a particular $F(s)$ is not in the Laplace Transform table, Partial Fraction Expansion (PFE) is used to break $F(s)$ into a sum of simpler components with known Laplace transforms: $F(s)=F_{1}(s)+F_{2}(s)+\dots+F_{n}(s)$. Because the inverse Laplace transform is linear, each term can then be inverted independently: $f(t)=\mathcal{L}^{-1}[F_{1}(s)]+\mathcal{L}^{-1}[F_{2}(s)]+\dots+\mathcal{L}^{-1}[F_{n}(s)]$. PFE requires writing $F(s)$ as a ratio of two polynomials, $\frac{p(s)}{q(s)}$.', '[-0.03134001,0.030661793,-0.036272213,0.012980701,0.023510383,0.0035800957,0.07324917,0.019290281,0.004676712,0.012930166,-0.038980078,0.0143329045,-0.026745178,0.030873436,0.012144102,0.013720452,0.034843337,0.014402274,0.04576201,-0.03155697,0.0072727986,0.009815859,-0.028074944,-0.008167809,0.0052349325,0.013281996,-0.008474065,0.0077540707,0.04930659,-0.001976741,-0.003997923,-0.005554747,-0.001628134,-0.05629384,-0.025384918,0.02659745,0.0029174974,-0.030324655,-0.04104828,-0.018546691,-0.04774048,-0.024064083,0.019867428,0.00095933524,0.012517663,-0.022426728,-0.0027936352,-0.0478518,-0.023450471,-0.04855291,-0.0051648575,-0.022095403,0.09145138,-0.031152517,-0.018974597,0.009181507,-0.041148245,-0.017977266,-0.08915046,-0.02462347,-0.027824828,0.011146109,-0.05225787,0.012835311,0.037992544,-0.009748288,-0.006684971,0.031403735,0.0018991274,-0.02279034,-0.013237597,0.029104607,-0.026050892,-0.033692934,-0.0577549,0.08418881,-0.0038572468,0.021805428,-0.012250684,0.06063158,0.006232487,-0.