INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (50, 17, 'This chunk introduces the concept of Transfer Functions (TF) in Process Control, contrasting them with nonlinear ODEs and highlighting their advantages for control system design. Modeling activities often lead to sets of nonlinear ordinary differential equations (ODEs), which are difficult to work with and may not yield analytical solutions. A preferred alternative is the transfer function model, which is based on Laplace transforms. Although transfer functions contain the same information as linearized ODEs, they are preferred because they are independent of the input function and allow the process response to an input change to be generalized. They play a key role in control system design and analysis, and characterize the dynamic relationship between a dependent output variable and an independent input variable. Transfer functions are strictly applicable only to processes exhibiting linear dynamic behavior; for nonlinear processes, they provide an approximate linear model.', '[-0.07110316,-0.00052376784,-0.060390558,0.033840697,0.023401203,-0.0029485617,0.015973695,0.05743828,0.020975031,0.04135749,-0.048433203,-0.020640252,0.0003168599,0.036591414,0.003151626,0.025533367,0.025793443,-0.017533211,0.009001785,-0.0070869927,0.015937319,0.020305732,0.005521414,-0.011963156,-0.012122148,0.026435085,-0.0034407412,-0.061676987,-0.020941403,0.025727244,0.02476062,0.022621112,-0.037813473,-0.026100751,-0.025731703,0.02268823,0.023309818,-0.053822525,-0.036354713,-0.021408096,-0.02406787,-0.036836486,0.032664776,-0.0036385593,0.029224379,-0.010252459,-0.00046888893,-0.045540888,-0.04381687,-0.023622429,0.010925797,-0.054133557,0.062543206,-0.03873076,0.017469184,0.033544976,-0.03234577,-0.035187602,-0.050675556,0.0024579763,-0.036865458,-0.0022736175,0.0073716966,-0.023671512,0.029244658,-0.011305493,-0.027160155,0.016308755,-0.0011557987,-0.07301702,0.023523148,0.0041753403,-0.031891357,-0.029220037,-0.037915006,0.068270996,-0