INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (56, 18, 'This chunk defines the first property of transfer function model, Steady-State Gain (K), explains how to calculate it from both data and the transfer function itself. The Steady-State Gain ($K$) represents the ratio of the change in output to the change in input once the system has reached a new steady state. For an input change from $\overline{u}_1$ to $\overline{u}_2$ and a corresponding output change from $\overline{y}_1$ to $\overline{y}_2$, the gain is calculated as: $$K=\frac{\overline{y}_{2}-\overline{y}_{1}}{\overline{u}_{2}-\overline{u}_{1}}$$ For a linear system, $K$ is constant. However, for a nonlinear system, $K$ will depend on the specific operating condition $(\overline{u}, \overline{y})$. Mathematically, if a transfer function model $G(s)$ has a steady-state gain, it can be found using the Final Value Theorem: $$K=\lim_{s\rightarrow0}G(s)$$. Note that some transfer function models, such as integrating processes, do not have a steady-state gain.', '[-0.045279227,0.02212988,-0.072813496,0.020831835,-0.009149507,-0.0015258482,0.006892015,0.05754769,0.031241348,0.03118183,0.0040820893,0.0065042996,-0.011046025,0.031985253,0.015516367,0.009916453,-0.0025612474,0.018893953,-0.025195794,-0.01884924,0.0044472143,-0.020737864,0.043050222,0.028607026,0.016300643,0.025421368,0.007855143,-0.031474836,0.0115960585,0.065736026,0.03149777,0.01709038,-0.05013421,-0.039653957,-0.03906513,0.05169226,-0.014531651,-0.031209847,-0.029816758,0.08772935,0.0071634,-0.019913947,0.015390914,-0.061074294,0.06276377,-0.018243454,0.0005502726,-0.042646244,-0.049976204,-0.009521255,0.0122916065,-0.023570886,0.036773693,-0.072730325,0.034600332,-0.003547166,-0.07671889,-0.007239869,-0.02467496,0.004933587,-0.05067279,0.082576334,-0.0069741732,0.011238719,0.035773356,-0.00052316114,0.02881149,0.03202796,-0.0022710722,-0.012534866,0.03218057,0.0415797,-0.058233827,-0.011070729,-0.03870025,0.012096723,0.023615327,-0.013837666,0.018672233,0