INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (59, 19, 'This chunk explains why linearization is necessary for chemical processes and introduces the first-order Taylor series expansion as the method for approximation. Most chemical processes are nonlinear, modeled by nonlinear differential equations that are difficult to solve. To design and analyze control systems, a linear approximation is often used. This approximation is most accurate near the specific point of linearization (the operating point). If nonlinear processes remain close to this operating point, the linear approximation is reasonably accurate. Moreover, a well-performing controller keeps the process close to the operating point. The linearization uses a first-order Taylor series expansion: $$y \approx f(x_{0})+\frac{df}{dx}|_{x=x_{0}}(x-x_{0})$$. Higher-order terms are neglected if the variation in $x$ is small, and this approximation is exact only at $x=x_0$. Note that large changes in operating conditions for a nonlinear process cannot be approximated satisfactorily by linear expressions.', '[-0.055728342,0.010536279,-0.049776293,-0.0152465645,0.0042701727,-0.012674759,-0.01671965,0.036618344,0.023167556,0.05086283,-0.02197236,-0.033233482,-0.014711597,-0.0019531907,-0.016214201,0.007054309,0.02090017,0.0063459105,0.03220405,-0.040783033,-0.03701866,-0.010999159,-0.009663424,0.002478549,-0.040536735,-0.008420986,-0.039042033,-0.002103758,0.019097753,0.0047425497,0.029388627,0.0025378305,-0.028966956,-0.018834924,-0.016798466,0.022253599,0.042933065,-0.043391,-0.009528627,0.020475077,0.0021819954,0.007196225,0.011845176,0.014704203,0.0046914457,-0.018764308,-0.022095315,-0.037151013,-0.027710136,-0.06636578,-0.005848166,-0.032727126,0.03801844,-0.025579227,-0.014198107,0.026809359,-0.05767259,-0.004641317,-0.054515462,0.027685216,-0.06622561,5.5741715e-05,-0.01345524,-0.026133193,0.02051412,0.0023342888,-0.013560249,0.051016327,0.016492646,-0.045235172,0.009914626,0.04178404,-0.033294402,-0.013187275,-0.052068