INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (70, 21, 'This chunk uses a question example to discuss the effects of $K$ and $\tau$ on the response. Consider two first order processes: $G_1(s) = \frac{K_1}{\tau_1 s + 1}$ and $G_2(s) = \frac{K_2}{\tau_2 s + 1}$. The step response of $G_1(s)$ reaches 50% of its ultimate value in 10 min. When will the step response of $G_2(s)$ reach 50% of its ultimate value given Case 1: $K_2 = 2K_1$ and $\tau_1 = \tau_2$ and Case 2: $K_2 = K_1$ and $\tau_1 = 2\tau_2$?" For a first-order process with the transfer function $G(s) = \frac{K}{\tau s + 1}$, the time required to reach a certain percentage of its ultimate value is solely determined by the time constant ($\tau$), not the process gain ($K$). For Case 1: the process gain for $G_2(s)$ is doubled, so its ultimate value will be twice as large as that of $G_1(s)$ for the same input. However, because the time constants are identical ($\tau_1 = \tau_2$), the speed of the response is unchanged, so $G_2(s)$ will also reach 50% of its (larger) ultimate value in exactly 10 minutes. For Case 2: the time constant for $G_2(s)$ is doubled ($\tau_2 = 2\tau_1$), so $G_2(s)$ will take twice as long as $G_1(s)$ to reach the 50% mark, resulting in a time of 20 minutes.', '[-0.032542787,0.018880982,-0.03821728,0.0066603846,-0.022519361,-0.027408402,0.014659358,0.02312054,0.028058633,0.033377953,-0.003716186,-0.0182055,-0.0005416879,0.025739562,0.03509022,0.036658287,0.0200135,0.0032972503,-0.0135991555,-0.029393833,-0.002164176,0.008809379,-0.002701416,0.018242553,0.026277171,0.011380859,-0.055351786,2.6297406e-05,0.03581971,0.046586666,-9.937381e-05,0.0136328265,-0.02009799,-0.0644523,-0.03002502,0.037698884,0.027341673,-0.01652114,-0.029321114,0.063168965,0.00062870013,-0.0049467017,0.020482544,-0.043792743,0.027711656,0.016391736,-0.020048657,-0.056013707,-0.02676523,-0.031000286,0.00261725,-0.051475644,0.0022076198,-0.011328901,0.032357026,0.040579543,-0.03874087,0.028417654,-0.042088754,-0.011231704,-0.