INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (74, 23, 'This chunk describes the origins of second-order transfer functions, explaining how they arise from either two first-order processes connected in series or directly from the transformation of a second-order ordinary differential equation. A second-order transfer function can arise whenever two first-order processes are connected in series. For example, in a system of two stirred-tank blending processes, the output of the first tank serves as the input to the second. The overall transfer function $G(s)$ is the product of the individual first-order functions: $G(s) = \frac{Y(s)}{U(s)} = \frac{X(s)}{U(s)}\frac{Y(s)}{X(s)} = \frac{K_{1}K_{2}}{(\tau_{1}s+1)(\tau_{2}s+1)}$. Alternatively, a second-order process transfer function arises upon transforming a second-order ordinary differential equation of the form $\tau^{2}\frac{d^{2}y(t)}{dt^{2}}+2\zeta\tau\frac{dy(t)}{dt}+y(t)=Ku(t)$. Applying the Laplace transform to this equation yields the standard second-order transfer function: $G(s)=\frac{K}{\tau^{2}s^{2}+2\zeta\tau s+1}$.', '[-0.05372196,0.0021467844,-0.04652965,0.026697502,0.016083093,-0.0017021829,-0.033552434,0.043824505,0.024434574,0.010256921,-0.012544234,-0.017975694,-0.026616039,0.044983108,0.03319871,0.022372825,0.028469985,0.034076434,-0.022567816,0.0076602916,-0.0020743273,0.0064836787,0.00231951,-0.009262173,-0.03777593,0.04112083,-0.020461531,-0.04755945,0.014652074,0.008699211,0.017644623,-0.009257139,-0.049708873,-0.043733947,-0.027408574,0.039089818,0.013781919,-0.0007621278,-0.03827253,0.049579356,-0.03051911,0.0026061332,0.041912336,-0.059094578,0.031135993,0.007395435,-0.00509613,-0.034204286,-0.05186757,-0.04150083,-0.017065842,-0.048827473,0.060702328,-0.03807083,-0.0051047322,0.020348145,-0.04553945,0.012689318,-0.038237985,-0.023386734,-0.033229034,0.055640366,-0.0023188768,0.0029587927,0.029310502,0.008947544,-0.001599655,0.023014449,-0.0153273875,-0.037302174,-0.008612952,0.040596407,-0.03144628,0.0