INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (76, 23, 'This chunk classifies second-order processes into three distinct cases based on the value of the damping factor and the nature of the roots of the characteristic equation. The dynamic behavior of a second-order process is categorized into three distinct cases depending on the value of the damping factor $\zeta$. When $\zeta > 1$, the characteristic equation $\tau^{2}s^{2}+2\zeta\tau s+1=0$ has distinct real roots, and the response is classified as non-oscillatory or overdamped. This type of response is initially delayed compared to a first-order process and becomes increasingly sluggish as the damping factor increases, eventually approaching its final value of $KM$ asymptotically as time approaches infinity. When $\zeta = 1$, the roots are real and equal, resulting in a critically damped response. This response is also non-oscillatory and is characterized by a rapid approach to the final value without any oscillations. When $0 \le \zeta < 1$, the characteristic equation has complex conjugate roots, and the response is classified as underdamped or oscillatory. In this case, the response is initially faster, but the amount of oscillation increases as the damping factor decreases.', '[-0.067348726,-0.03485142,0.006360947,0.022716522,-0.017452106,-0.03743685,0.013973314,0.019241666,0.004083996,0.030289812,-0.0012324644,-0.021797817,-0.008722393,-0.01893529,0.04333012,0.02955136,-0.013299531,0.008961061,-0.020006428,0.007735674,-0.026057282,0.000693977,-0.019352717,-0.0129575385,-0.06434461,0.022699874,-0.0314327,-0.027731914,0.004849456,0.051236633,0.015093667,0.023332607,0.0020926092,-0.050022397,-0.047702014,-0.018111033,0.010704584,-0.044236597,-0.031574946,-0.006064195,-0.004401013,0.006121659,0.026049614,-0.016966172,0.06473439,0.019663827,-0.0073014717,-0.050911155,-0.011964954,-0.046673875,-0.0137232775,-0.03896593,0.04101981,-0.022128327,0.012927385,0.03315812,-0.028000474,-0.010628935,-0.0564992,0.014676787,0.0007063