INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (90, 25, 'This chunk summarizes the fundamental requirements for the stability of linear dynamic systems based on pole locations. A linear dynamic system is stable if and only if all of its poles have negative real parts. Even if one pole has a positive real part, the entire system is unstable. These conclusions hold even when the system has repeated complex poles. Importantly, the locations of the zeros in a transfer function have no effect on the stability of the process. Stability of linear systems can be visualized in the complex plane, where the horizontal axis is the real part (Re) and the vertical axis is the imaginary part (Im). The left-half plane represents the stable region, while the right-half plane is the unstable region. The imaginary axis denotes marginally stable systems. Based on these principles, the stability of various systems can be evaluated with the following examples: A system defined by the equation $\frac{1}{(s-1)}$ is unstable because its pole is on the right half of the plane. A system defined by the equation $\frac{1}{(s^{2}+s+1)}$ is stable because all its poles are strictly in the left half of the plane. Similarly, a system defined by the equation $\frac{(s-10)}{(s^{2}+s+1)}$ remains stable because all its poles are strictly in the left half of the plane. However, a system like $\frac{(s-10)}{s(s+1)}$ has a pole at zero, which is considered marginally stable, thus it is simply classified as unstable.', '[-0.05514733,-0.01946735,-0.034485273,0.02623001,0.011714924,-0.031650893,0.015494108,0.05214302,-0.019225439,0.024427304,-0.024373984,-0.009900875,-0.004093494,0.029073475,0.0009256506,0.020558732,0.008366152,0.006981973,-0.016729787,-0.007008811,-0.0066426992,-0.026311805,0.013229722,-0.01564979,-0.019756122,0.022405215,-0.04324887,0.040491745,0.005030756,0.08221149,-0.03192083,0.042910304,-0.005315145,-0.036726974,-0.02457465,0.013830384,-0.003857912,-0.04413962,-0.0242608,0.015381143,-0.023187496,