INSERT INTO document_chunks VALUES (100, 28, 'This chunk explains the motivation for approximating higher-order transfer functions with lower-order models, noting the sluggish nature of high-order responses and introducing the Taylor series expansion as a mathematical tool for approximation. Most chemical processes possess very high-order dynamics due to factors such as imperfect mixing, wall effects, and flow dynamics, or simply because they consist of multiple units like tanks in series. The transfer function for such a system is typically represented as the product of many first-order terms, taking the form $G(s)=\frac{K}{(\tau_{1}s+1)(\tau_{2}s+1).....(\tau_{n}s+1)}$. Unlike simple first or second-order processes, it is difficult to draw general dynamic insights from these high-order models. As the order of the system increases, the step response becomes progressively more sluggish, and the apparent delay in the response increases significantly. To facilitate more convenient control system design and analysis, these high-order functions are approximated using lower-order models. A key mathematical tool in this approximation is the Taylor series expansion. The transfer function for a time delay can be approximated by truncating the series, where $e^{-\theta_{0}s}\approx1-\theta_{0}s$. This relationship allows small time constants or lags in the denominator to be effectively converted into a time delay term in the numerator.', '[-0.07515099,-0.009537281,-0.06470483,0.018049983,-0.00090018514,-0.012504324,-0.033230502,0.017294353,-0.010217418,0.047303423,-0.019488605,-0.00953613,-0.034941003,0.017381486,-0.0019178557,0.002140973,0.022111561,0.024411175,0.024093708,-0.015989255,-0.013635991,0.01483968,0.00075333123,0.011458814,-0.03044137,0.018926978,-0.04089337,-0.010564959,0.015834011,0.014493898,0.03008211,0.0009640885,-0.01699155,-0.007777176,-0.023265284,0.041361332,0.037272096,-0.05854392,-0.022981571,0.04939724,-0.017821606,-0.025601171,-0.006962756,-0.038642